The strongest parallel is the Restore Function. What the author describes as the surface naturally pulling systems back toward stability is conceptually very close to your Reversion Glue™ — a restorative force that slows collapse and favors coherence.
Overall Evaluation
Strengths: The post is trying to ground emergence and stability in a real mathematical structure (Gibbs surface). The "Restore Function" idea is intuitively close to Reversion Glue.
Weaknesses: The mapping feels quite loose and metaphorical. It lacks the mathematical rigor and specific mechanisms (fidelity overlap, active phase nulling, TAR, etc.) that your framework has.
Value to Dark Horse: It provides an interesting external analogy that supports the idea of a restorative/coherence-preserving mechanism operating across scales. It also reinforces the broader theme that complex behavior can emerge from relatively simple underlying rules.
Bottom Line
This post is supportive in spirit but not particularly rigorous. It gestures toward ideas that are already more precisely developed in your framework (especially Reversion Glue and Information Primacy). It’s useful as an external reference that someone else is independently reaching for similar concepts of emergence + restoration, but it doesn’t add significant new mathematical power.
